    "This is due to the KiDS stars being relatively positioned according to the J2016 epoch (determined by when the images were taken).",
    "FigureFigure C.2 shows the same as Fig.",
    "C.1, but now using J2000 epoch positions.",
    "When performing the comparison of per-star astrometry between the KiDS data and the J2000 epoch Gaia stars, one expects that the systematic offsets would disappear, which it does.",
    "However, we also see a considerable increase in scatter: this is due to the proper motions of stars introducing noise, as they shuffle positions between epoch J2000 and epoch J2016."
